Tree-Based Models (Bagging, Boosting and Random Forest)

About

Tree-Based Model is also called Classification and Regression Trees (CART). It is considered to be one of the best and mostly used supervised learning methods. Tree based algorithms empower predictive models with high accuracy, stability and ease of interpretation. This method construct more powerful predictive models for regression and classification problems. The idea of these techniques combine the decisions from multiple models to improve the overall performance as they minimize factors of noise, bias and variances to improve the stability and accuracy of any models. For this section, we will focus on ensemble methods of tree-based model like Bagging, Boosting and Random forest to build a strong models.

Ensemble Techniques

An ensemble method is a technique that combines the predictions from multiple machine learning algorithms together to make more accurate predictions than any individual model. A Tree-based algorithm also suffers from the plague of bias and variance. Bias means, how much on an average are the predicted values different from the actual value. Variance means, how different will the predictions of the model be at the same point if different samples are taken from the same population. When we build a small tree and and get a model with low variance and high bias or what is known as bias-variance tradeoff, this is when the ensembling techniques comes into play.

Bagging

Bagging also called Bootstrap aggregating. Bagging is a general-purpose procedure for reducing the variance of a statistical learning method and helps to avoid overfitting. It is achieved by creating random samples of the training dataset with replacement and building model for each sample. The result of these multiple models are combined using average or multiple voting. It is given by,

where B is the different boostrapped training dataset and $^{fb}(x)$ is the trained method of the $B^{th}$ bootrapped training set and the average of all the predictions is what we called Bagging.

To apply Bagging to predict a qualitative outcome Y in the classification context, the class that is predicted by each of the $B^{th}$ trees for a given test observation has to be recorded. The most commonly occuring majority class among the $B^{th}$ predictions is the overall prediction.

To apply Bagging to predict a continuous outcome Y in the regression context, which is mostly useful in decision tree, the B regression trees has to be constructed using $B^{th}$ bootstrapped training set and average the resulting prediction.

                                                Bagging in practice

Boosting

Boosting is also an ensemble technique and it refers to a group of algorithms that utilize weighted averages to make weak learners into stronger learners. Unlike bagging that had each model run independently and then aggregate the outputs at the end without preference to any model. Boosting is all about teamwork. Each model that runs, dictates what features the next model will focus on. Boosting takes this concept much further and fits a series of models with each successive model fit to minimize the error of the previous models. Boosting is a sequential technique in which, the first algorithm is trained on the entire data set and the subsequent algorithms are built by fitting the residuals of the first algorithm, thus giving higher weight to those observations that were poorly predicted by the previous model. It has shown to provide better predictive accuracy than Bagging. It is given by,

where M is the maximum number of model to be fit, $\hat{f}_i$ is a trained model. The shrinkage parameter $\alpha$, a small positive number. This controls the rate at which boosting learns. Typical values are 0.01 or 0.001, and the right choice can depend on the problem. For each model, it could be calculated with log 1 minus weighted error devided by the weighted error.

                                                Boosting in practice

Random Forest

Random forests or random decision forests is also an ensemble learning method for classification, regression and other algorithm methods.It also undertakes dimensional reduction methods, treats missing values, outlier values and other essential steps of data exploration, and does a fairly good job. It is a type of ensemble learning method, where a group of weak models combine to form a powerful model. The forest it builds is an ensemble of decisions trees. It basically constructs a multitude of decision trees at training time and merge them together to get more accurate and stable prediction of the class that is the mode of the classes (classification) or mean prediction (regression) of the individual trees. making the average of the resulting trees less variable and hence more reliable. Random forests provide an improvement over bagged trees by way of a random small tweak that decorrelates the trees. It is given by,

For regression, $T(x;\theta_b)$ is the grown trees and B is the different boostrapped training dataset.

If for regression $T(x;\theta_b)$ is the grown trees, in classification $C_b(x)$ is the class prediction of the $B^{th}$ random forest.

                                            Random Forest in practice

Data pre-processing

In[8]:
publishers = pd.get_dummies(vgsales_data["Publisher"], drop_first=True)
genres = pd.get_dummies(vgsales_data["Genre"], drop_first=True)
platforms = pd.get_dummies(vgsales_data["Platform"], drop_first=True)
names = pd.get_dummies(vgsales_data["Name"], drop_first=True)

vgsales_data = pd.concat([vgsales_data, publishers, genres, platforms,names ], axis=1)
vgsales_data = vgsales_data.drop(columns=["Platform","Genre", "Publisher", "Name", "NA_Sales", "EU_Sales", "JP_Sales", "Other_Sales" ])

Conclusion

The vgsales dataset was used to apply tree-based modelling. All the 16000 observations were used in predicting video games in the global market given it's rank, name, platform, genre and publisher. Decision tree, bagging, boosting and random forest methods have been use to contruct strong models to predict global market sales of all video games in general. The below is the summary of how each model perform in the dataset.

Decision tree:

  • r2: 0.9976799285642691
  • mse: 0.005676373120589143

Bagging:

  • r2: 0.9995007759797592
  • mse: 0.001221420067505375

Boosting:

  • r2: 0.992549205308933
  • mse: 0.01822939158684941

Random Forest:

  • r2: 0.999321920541168
  • mse: 0.0016590144400123069

The r2 of each of the models is almost 100% which means that the tree-models explain the variance of our data. And as we can see in the graph of each of the tree-based methods, the predicted value in color blue almost prefectly captures the true value of the global market sales in color red. This implies one thing that tree-based methods in regression is a very powerful model.
